Phase 1: Deploy Your Web Application
Before creating an Android app, your Next.js app needs to be hosted publicly on the internet.

Push your code to a GitHub repository.
Deploy the app using a hosting provider like Vercel or Google Cloud Run. These services natively support Next.js and will give your app a live public URL (e.g., https://stellaris-hrm.vercel.app).
Phase 2: Convert to an Android App
Once your web app is live, you can transform it into an Android app. The easiest and most modern method recommended by Google is using Bubblewrap (which creates a Trusted Web Activity).

Prerequisites: You will need to have Node.js and the Java Development Kit (JDK) installed.

Step 1: Install Bubblewrap CLI Open your terminal and run the following command to install Google's Bubblewrap globally:

bash
npm install -g @bubblewrap/cli
Step 2: Initialize the Android Project Create a new folder for your mobile app, navigate into it, and initialize Bubblewrap using your live website's URL:

bash
mkdir stellaris-android
cd stellaris-android
bubblewrap init --manifest https://your-hosted-app-url.com/manifest.json
(Note: Ensure your Next.js app has a basic manifest.json file in the public folder defining the app's name, icons, and theme colors. Bubblewrap relies on this)

Step 3: Build the App Bundle Once initialized, you can build the Android App Bundle (.aab) which is the format Google Play requires:

bash
bubblewrap build
During this process, Bubblewrap will ask you to create a "Keystore" (a secure file used to cryptographically sign your app). Store this Keystore password safely. It will successfully generate an .aab file in your folder.

Phase 3: Publish to Google Play Store
Create a Google Play Developer Account (Requires a one-time $25 registration fee).
Go to the Play Console and click Create App. Fill in the name, default language, and categorize it as an "App."
Set up your store listing by providing your app's descriptions, screenshots, and an app icon.
On the left menu, navigate to Production under the "Release" section.
Click Create new release and upload the .aab (Android App Bundle) file you generated in Phase 2.
Submit your app for review! Google typically takes between 1-3 days to review and publish the app.

